data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | **Timeout enforcement** | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | **Control flow** | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Continue execution** | Remove — not needed with cooperative model |

### Why It Breaks

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006`). The fundamental shift is from **preemptive** cancellation (runtime injects an exception) to **cooperative** cancellation (code voluntarily checks a token).

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // Task.Run + CancellationTokenSource replaces Thread + Abort
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Overload accepting a CancellationToken so callers can
    // also cancel from outside, not just on timeout.
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout,
        CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
            when (externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Caller cancelled — let it propagate as-is
            throw;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
            when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | What to do |
|---------|------------|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | The `work` delegate won't be interrupted mid-execution. If `work` is a tight CPU loop, it runs to completion even after timeout. Pass the token into `work` and call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer leaks. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the orchestration boundary. The `when` guard distinguishes timeout vs. external cancellation. |
| **`Task.Run` doesn't guarantee a new thread** | It uses the ThreadPool, which is usually better. But if `work` blocks a pool thread for a long time, it can starve the pool. For truly long-blocking work, consider `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning`. |
| **Uncooperative code** | If `work` calls code you can't modify (e.g., a native/third-party blocking call), cooperative cancellation won't help. Move that work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` on timeout — that's the only safe forced-termination mechanism in modern .NET. |

### What Was Removed

| Removed | Replacement |
|---------|-------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` (via timeout) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Deleted — cooperative model doesn't need it |
| Manual `new Thread(...)` | `Task.Run` on the thread pool |
